{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17476102","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17476102"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:40:42+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:40:42+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13181"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13181","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13181"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.02,0.77,0.16,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5617"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55619"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5617","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5617"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13181"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41160"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"13"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1954"},{"type":"tags","id":"3749"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4965"},{"type":"tags","id":"4969"},{"type":"tags","id":"4970"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"9569"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9630"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11785"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17180"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44145"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55619","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/55619"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA five-year-old boy presents to the Emergency Department with a four-hour history of spontaneous painful penile erection. He has been unwell for the past five days with shortness of breath, chest pain and fever. He and his family recently migrated from Nigeria. He has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears pale with a pulse rate of 120/min, blood pressure 100/60 mmHg, respiratory rate 24/min, SpO2 96% on room air, and temperature 38.2\u00b0C. The penile shaft is rigid and tender. Other examination findings are unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInvestigations reveal:\u003Cbr /\u003EHaemoglobin 80 g/L (110-135)\u003Cbr /\u003EWhite cell count 11 x 10\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E/L (4-10)\u003Cbr /\u003EPlatelets 350 x 10\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E/L (150-400)\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHis peripheral blood smear is shown (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely underlying cause of his current presentation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Thalassaemia","Leukaemia","Sickle cell anaemia","Malaria","Pelvic trauma"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis boy has priapism, defined as a persistent penile erection unrelated to sexual interest or desire. In children, \u003Cstrong\u003Esickle cell anaemia\u003C/strong\u003E is the most common cause, accounting for 65% of cases. The associated presenting features of chest pain and shortness of breath, along with sickle-shaped red cells on the peripheral blood smear, strongly suggest sickle cell disease as the underlying diagnosis in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELeukaemia\u003C/strong\u003E is the second most common cause of priapism in children, responsible for around 10% of cases. However, the peripheral blood smear is not consistent with leukaemia, which would typically show immature white blood cells (blasts).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThalassaemia\u003C/strong\u003E is another haemoglobinopathy that can occasionally cause priapism. However, the peripheral blood smear would typically show microcytic, hypochromic red cells rather than sickle cells. Additionally, thalassaemia is less common in individuals of African descent compared to sickle cell disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMalaria\u003C/strong\u003E is a consideration given the patient\u0027s recent migration from Nigeria, an endemic area. While malaria can cause anaemia and fever, it is not typically associated with priapism. The peripheral blood smear would show parasites within red blood cells rather than sickle cells.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPelvic trauma\u003C/strong\u003E can potentially cause priapism, but there is no history of trauma mentioned in this case. Additionally, trauma would not explain the other symptoms or the abnormal blood smear.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPriapism is a medical emergency that requires timely diagnosis and appropriate management to prevent permanent damage due to ischaemia and erectile dysfunction. Screening for sickle cell disease with haemoglobin electrophoresis to demonstrate the presence or increased quantity of haemoglobin S would be indicated.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Sickle cell disease is the most common cause of priapism in children.","Priapism is a medical emergency that requires timely diagnosis and management to prevent permanent damage and erectile dysfunction.","Peripheral blood smear showing sickle cells is suggestive of sickle cell disease."],"references":["Idris IM, Burnett AL, DeBaun MR. Epidemiology and treatment of priapism in sickle cell disease. Hematology Am Soc Hematol Educ Program. 2022 Dec 9;2022(1):450-458.","Silberman M, Stormont G, Leslie SW, Hu EW. Priapism. 2023 May 30. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2023 Jan\u2013. PMID: 29083574.","Ericson C, Baird B, Broderick GA. Management of Priapism: 2021 Update. Urol Clin North Am. 2021 Nov;48(4):565-576. doi: 10.1016/j.ucl.2021.07.003. Epub 2021 Aug 25. PMID: 34602176."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41160"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13181"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20310"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20310","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20310"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/ZgTlB02P5Lep9Pqie3qKEoXcAY7ebo.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/ZgTlB02P5Lep9Pqie3qKEoXcAY7ebo.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":1002,"height":618}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41160","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/41160"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-17T09:00:25+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-17T09:00:25+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5617"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55619"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"13","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/13"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\ude78","name":"Haematology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"gro